			<ns0:name>kschi...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/108470876877739532758/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">As per meeting on 9/25/2012, simplifying this to allow reads of r9 under the assumption that we will use a random pointer (generated in trusted code) to implement r9. Hence, even though it is readable, no real information is given away.

Note: This decision was based on the fact that to make r9 unreadable required a lot of work in the ARM validator. In particular, it required implementing a "uses" virtual for all class decoders (which defines how each instruction is modeled).</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-09-26T19:33:24.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-09-26T19:33:24.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 6 by kschi...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=2933#c6" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/2933/comments/full/6" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>